    <title>Combined summary - BIP 21 (modification BIP 20)</title>
    <updated>2023-06-05T02:10:45.034774+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2012-January/001102.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>The email exchange revolves around the Bitcoin Improvement Proposal (BIP) 21 and BIP 20. The main difference between the two proposals is how they standardize the "amount" field, with BIP 20 proposing allowing alternative representations of the amount, while BIP 21 requires the use of a single representation in decimal notation. There is a general consensus that BIP 21 is better because it reduces complexity at both human and machine levels. However, there are debates on features like the "send to private address" field and the "expires" field.There is a discussion about whether a dual representation (block or timestamp) should be included for the "expires" field. The "version" field is deemed redundant, and the URI signing mechanism needs more work before being included in a dedicated BIP. The standard for treating unknown URL parameters is also discussed, and the suggestion is to define the standard upfront rather than refusing all unknown parameters.Gavin Andresen expresses his preference for BIP 21 over BIP 20, stating that "simpler is better." He also endorses the idea of signing and dating URIs but suggests waiting until there is consensus around BIP 21 before pursuing it. Matt Corallo submits a modification to BIP 20 excluding non-decimal number components, and discussions are ongoing about which BIP to support and how to handle unknown URL parameters.The MultiBit team supports BIP 21 and plans to add "message" or "send" fields if required. They also propose adding an "expires" field to the BIP 21 proposal. The idea of a signed URI is considered but has some disadvantages, and the MultiBit team suggests using an "expires" field instead. The comparison between BIP 20 and BIP 21 is also discussed, with BIP 21 being preferred because it reduces complexity at both human and machine levels.Wladimir suggests that the BIP should only define the URL scheme and leave room for future extensions such as send-to-private-address and send-multiple-signers. The extensions should be forwards-compatible, meaning older clients can detect schemes they don't understand and give appropriate error messages. A versioning scheme is proposed where any BIP breaking backwards compatibility should increase the version number, and clients reject URLs with a higher version number.Overall, the goal is to achieve a general consensus on the standard for Bitcoin Improvement Proposals. The GUI client implementations of the BIP are considered important, with more weight given to those with actual URI scheme implementations. The author plans to ask GUI client implementations such as MultiBit or Bitcoin-Qt if they support BIP 20 or BIP 21, and more weight will be given to GUIs with actual URI scheme implementations. The email ends with a promotion for the online learning library, LearnDevNow.</summary>
